CHAPTER 1
The Extended Kalman Filter
Contributed by J. Russell Carpenter

As described in the preface, use of the Extended Kalman Filter (EKF) for navigation has a long history of ﬂight-proven success. The EKF thus forms the foundational best practice advocated by this work, and it forms the basis for many of the best practices later chapters describe. The purpose of the present chapter is not to derive the EKF and its relations, but rather to present them in a basic form, as a jumping o↵ point for the rest of the material we shall present. As we shall show, while the EKF is a powerful and robust algorithm, it is based on a few ad hoc assumptions, which can lead to misuses and misunderstandings. Many of the best practices we shall describe are tricks of the trade that address such issues.

